data.content:
Your code doesn't actually use `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

That said, for .NET 8 modernization, consider replacing raw threads with `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you better thread pool utilization and a natural path to cancellation via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
